### Example 13.2: A Drifting Dot

State can be anything. Here, state is a position vector `(x y)`. Each frame, the dot drifts right and down.

```scheme
(define (tick pos)
  (let ([x (car pos)]
        [y (cadr pos)])
    (list (+ x 0.1) (+ y 0.05))))

(define (draw pos)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/spawn (car pos) (cadr pos) 'dot)
  pos)

(big-bang (list 8.0 4.0)
  [on-tick tick]
  [to-draw draw]
  [stop-when (lambda (pos) (> (car pos) 72.0))])
```

**Key insight:** `to-draw` resets the world and spawns the dot at the new position each frame. The *state* is the position; the *world* is ephemeral, rebuilt each frame. This is a valid (if inefficient) pattern for simple sketches.

[VISUAL: A dot starting at center-left, drifting diagonally right-down across the canvas, stopping at the right edge.]

<!-- BUILD: wire Example 13.2 runnable; ensure world/reset! clears entities before spawn. -->

